WEBVTT

00:01.760 --> 00:04.069
Let's do open discussion
before we wrap up.

00:04.100 --> 00:06.261
I have kind of a, uh,

00:06.300 --> 00:08.530
different topic in mind.

00:08.570 --> 00:12.176
Craziest thoughts
about your disease?

00:12.210 --> 00:13.438
You know what I mean.

00:13.480 --> 00:15.300
You know they're nuts,

00:15.340 --> 00:17.501
but they just keep popping
into your head aanay.

00:17.550 --> 00:21.008
I often wonder ifI should have
been born in another time.

00:21.750 --> 00:23.615
(clears throat)

00:23.650 --> 00:25.811
Sorry, my name is Sherlock,
and I'm an addict.

00:25.850 --> 00:27.511
ALL:
Hi, Sherlock.

00:27.560 --> 00:30.085
My-my...

00:30.130 --> 00:32.724
My senses are unusually--

00:32.760 --> 00:37.163
well, one could even say
unnaturally-- keen.

00:37.200 --> 00:39.065
(coughing)

00:39.100 --> 00:41.637
And ours is an era
of distraction.

00:41.670 --> 00:44.503
It's, uh, a punishing drumbeat

00:44.540 --> 00:47.407
of constant input.

00:47.440 --> 00:50.375
This-this cacophony

00:50.410 --> 00:53.208
which follows us into our homes

00:53.250 --> 00:55.309
and into our beds

00:55.350 --> 00:58.842
and seeps into our...

00:58.890 --> 01:00.858
into our souls,

01:00.890 --> 01:03.279
for want of a better word.

01:06.600 --> 01:08.397
For a long time, uh,

01:08.430 --> 01:11.399
there was only one poultice
for my raw nerve endings,

01:11.430 --> 01:14.831
and that was,
uh, copious drug use.

01:17.440 --> 01:19.237
So in my less
productive moments,

01:19.280 --> 01:21.669
I'm given to wonder...

01:25.350 --> 01:27.875
...if I'd just been born
when it was a little...

01:27.920 --> 01:31.447
quieter out there,

01:31.490 --> 01:35.312
would I have even become
an addict in the first place?

01:38.860 --> 01:42.364
Might I have been more focused?

01:44.800 --> 01:48.133
A more fully realized person?

01:48.170 --> 01:50.331
What, like Ancient Greece?

01:50.370 --> 01:51.769
You any idea what passed

01:51.810 --> 01:53.471
_ for dental _care
In the Hellenic era?

01:55.580 --> 01:57.775
No, no, I'd, um,

01:57.810 --> 02:01.416
I'd want some of the wonders
of modernity.

02:04.720 --> 02:07.553
Just before everything got...

02:07.590 --> 02:09.353
amplified.

02:09.390 --> 02:10.527
MAN:
Something like what?

02:10.560 --> 02:12.755
200 years ago?

02:16.200 --> 02:17.895
Mycroft.

02:17.930 --> 02:20.239
_ Web site said _
It was an open meeting.

02:20.270 --> 02:23.569
I came to support my brother,
so please go on.

02:23.610 --> 02:24.736
It's-it's fascinating.

02:24.770 --> 02:26.601
No. I, uh,

02:26.640 --> 02:29.245
I-I'm so sorry.

02:29.280 --> 02:31.271
Sorry.

02:34.980 --> 02:36.709
Hey, you leaving early?

02:36.750 --> 02:39.412
Did you really mean
what you said in there

02:39.460 --> 02:40.882
or were you just
winding them up?

02:40.920 --> 02:42.888
Mycroft.
I wouldn't have said
anything at all

02:42.930 --> 02:44.818
if I'd known the meeting
was compromised.

02:44.860 --> 02:47.249
Explain yourself!
Your maid told me
you'd gone out.

02:47.300 --> 02:48.949
I wheedled her a bit
to find out where.

02:49.000 --> 02:51.491
You live in England!
Did you know they've invented

02:51.530 --> 02:54.397
a flying conveyance capable
of hurtling its passengers

02:54.440 --> 02:55.668
vast distances.

02:55.700 --> 02:57.236
Ha.
Joan, delighted to see you.

02:57.270 --> 02:58.567
Oh, sorry.

02:58.610 --> 03:00.976
(chuckles)
Oh, dear.

03:01.010 --> 03:02.568
Um, so what are you doing
in New York?

03:02.610 --> 03:04.271
I planned to fly out next month.

03:04.310 --> 03:05.470
We're opening a branch

03:05.510 --> 03:06.977
of my restaurant Diogenes
in Tribeca.

03:07.020 --> 03:08.544
I intended to give you

03:08.580 --> 03:09.842
plenty of warning, of course,

03:09.890 --> 03:11.881
but, um, circumstances
brought me here earlier.

03:11.920 --> 03:13.785
Circumstances?

03:13.820 --> 03:14.582
Yes, a good friend of ours

03:14.620 --> 03:16.383
is in a bit of trouble,
Sherlock.

03:16.430 --> 03:18.250
We haven't got any
mutual friends.

03:18.290 --> 03:20.326
Acquaintance, then, might be
a better way of putting it.

03:20.360 --> 03:21.793
I'd like to explain it to you

03:21.830 --> 03:24.424
over dinner.
Oh.

03:26.970 --> 03:28.437
So we're planning on taking

03:28.470 --> 03:29.903
a couple of reservations
a night.

03:29.940 --> 03:31.737
The rest we'll fill
with walk-ins.

03:31.770 --> 03:34.409
I want the place
to be spontaneous, playful.

03:34.440 --> 03:37.443
Qualities you'll no doubt be
charging through the nose for.

03:37.480 --> 03:38.640
Oh, I think it's breathtaking.

03:38.680 --> 03:39.977
Thank you.
Once we've set the menu,

03:40.020 --> 03:41.817
we should be open
in a couple of weeks.

03:41.850 --> 03:42.782
I'm meeting with a couple

03:42.820 --> 03:44.242
of young chefs while I'm here.

03:44.290 --> 03:46.758
I want to find a new voice.

03:46.790 --> 03:48.849
Of course.

03:48.890 --> 03:51.427
"Old acquaintance"?

03:51.460 --> 03:53.451
Are you joking?

03:53.500 --> 03:54.751
Yes, well,
I thought it best explained

03:54.800 --> 03:57.360
by herself.

03:57.400 --> 04:00.369
Sherlock Holmes,
you look dashing as ever.

04:03.710 --> 04:06.907
Do let me know when you decide
to start aging, won't you?

04:08.810 --> 04:10.971
Well, I wasn't told
you'd be here.
Oh.

04:12.550 --> 04:15.371
Joan Watson, this
is Nigella Mason.

04:15.420 --> 04:16.785
She's my brother's
former fiance.

04:16.820 --> 04:18.515
Oh. Oh.

04:18.550 --> 04:20.313
It's nice to meet you.

04:20.360 --> 04:21.884
Lovely to meet you.

04:21.920 --> 04:23.922
Shall we?
Yes.

04:26.090 --> 04:27.648
WATSON:
I'm confused.

04:27.700 --> 04:29.520
Didn't you and your
brother's fiance...

04:29.570 --> 04:31.788
What? Copulate?

04:31.830 --> 04:34.435
Engage in several bouts
of vigorous sex?

04:34.470 --> 04:37.530
Yes, yes, we did.

05:01.600 --> 05:02.919
The plates are designed
to be shared,

05:02.970 --> 05:04.369
but pace yourself, okay?

05:04.400 --> 05:06.539
I've got a lot
of food back there.

05:06.570 --> 05:08.891
I know we're not serving
alcohol today.

05:08.940 --> 05:10.737
Are there any other
dietary restrictions?

05:10.770 --> 05:12.772
I lose my appetite

05:12.810 --> 05:14.835
in the company
of social-climbing trollops.

05:14.880 --> 05:15.904
WATSON:
Uh, no.

05:15.940 --> 05:17.441
Thank you, we're fine.

05:17.480 --> 05:19.368
NIGELLA:
I realize there's been

05:19.420 --> 05:20.944
some awkwardness
between the three of us.

05:20.980 --> 05:23.414
I seduced you within
weeks of your wedding

05:23.450 --> 05:25.509
and exposed your true
character to Mycroft.

05:25.550 --> 05:28.018
I cannot imagine how you've
managed to worm your way

05:28.060 --> 05:29.755
back into his life.

05:29.790 --> 05:31.826
It's complicated, Sherlock.

05:31.860 --> 05:34.658
A year after my difficulties

05:34.700 --> 05:37.669
with Mycroft, I fell in
love with and married

05:37.700 --> 05:39.793
a man by the name
of Robert Suffolk.

05:39.840 --> 05:42.092
He's also known by his title,

05:42.140 --> 05:43.960
the Marquess of Loudwater.

05:44.010 --> 05:45.136
"Marquess"?

05:45.170 --> 05:46.637
It's mid-level nobility.

05:46.680 --> 05:48.500
It's smack between
an earl and a duke.

05:48.540 --> 05:50.542
Oh, so that makes you a, um...

05:50.580 --> 05:52.104
Marchioness of Loudwater, yes.

05:52.150 --> 05:55.517
I retain my title though
I no longer retain my husband.

05:55.550 --> 05:57.541
The marquess turned out

05:57.590 --> 05:59.581
to be not as advertised.

05:59.620 --> 06:01.508
Not terribly interested
in holding up

06:01.560 --> 06:03.858
his end of the conjugal side,
if you follow.

06:03.890 --> 06:05.881
So...

06:05.930 --> 06:08.854
I turned, in my loneliness,
to Dalton,

06:08.900 --> 06:11.721
the man in charge of Robert's
stable of racehorses.

06:11.770 --> 06:13.499
I won't bore you
with the details,

06:13.540 --> 06:16.566
but private investigators
were hired,

06:16.610 --> 06:19.602
photographs were taken,
and the usual ugliness ensued.

06:19.640 --> 06:21.574
Do you see, finally,

06:21.610 --> 06:23.749
the magnitude of the
favor that I did you?

06:23.780 --> 06:26.146
While Robert
and I were courting,

06:28.980 --> 06:31.448
a champion stallion
named Silver Blaze,

06:31.490 --> 06:34.709
and thanks to the crafty work
of my lawyers,

06:34.760 --> 06:37.479
I came out of my marriage
with my title

06:37.530 --> 06:39.122
and ownership
of Silver Blaze.

06:39.160 --> 06:41.628
Now, he can't race anymore,
you understand.

06:41.660 --> 06:43.469
He's too old,

06:43.500 --> 06:46.663
but there is a thriving demand
for his studly services.

06:46.700 --> 06:48.588
So you've become a horse pimp?

06:48.640 --> 06:50.107
How fitting. Must be lucrative.

06:50.140 --> 06:53.906
Silver Blaze is being stabled
in Ulster County at the moment.

06:53.940 --> 06:55.908
The other night,

06:55.940 --> 06:57.544
Dalton was coming
to the stables

06:57.580 --> 07:00.469
to give the animal
his usual medication.

07:00.520 --> 07:03.739
He had a friend in the car,
and according to him,

07:03.790 --> 07:06.816
Dalton came upon a man who was
trying to break in the stables.

07:06.860 --> 07:08.987
Dalton confronted the burglar,

07:09.020 --> 07:10.851
and the man shot him.

07:10.890 --> 07:12.187
He died at the scene.

07:12.230 --> 07:13.697
I'm so sorry.

07:13.730 --> 07:14.697
Thank you.

07:14.730 --> 07:16.618
It's been awful.

07:16.670 --> 07:17.989
When the murderer fled,

07:18.030 --> 07:20.237
he left behind
a bag of supplies.

07:20.270 --> 07:22.864
The police found a syringe full

07:22.910 --> 07:24.764
of concentrated potassium,

07:24.810 --> 07:26.732
and they believe
that Dalton's killer

07:26.780 --> 07:29.476
intended to poison Silver Blaze.

07:29.510 --> 07:31.944
So you want us to find him
and protect your meal ticket?

07:31.980 --> 07:34.642
And get justice for Dalton.

07:34.680 --> 07:36.580
Look, I realize that I've made
some mistakes in my life,

07:36.620 --> 07:38.542
but I _have made efforts
to Improve myself,

07:38.590 --> 07:40.114
and when Mycroft fell sick,

07:40.160 --> 07:42.082
he found a way
to forgive me.

07:42.120 --> 07:43.656
Uh, Nigella, please.

07:43.690 --> 07:45.749
And I believe
that you can do the same.

07:47.600 --> 07:50.569
Oh, you didn't realize
that Mycroft was sick?

07:50.600 --> 07:52.966
Spot of leukemia.

07:53.000 --> 07:54.729
Bone marrow transplant.

07:54.770 --> 07:56.192
I'm better now.

07:56.240 --> 07:58.060
I tried to find different ways
to tell you.

07:58.110 --> 07:59.634
It just never happened.

08:01.840 --> 08:04.604
I'm sincerely sorry
for your troubles.

08:06.150 --> 08:07.674
But...

08:07.720 --> 08:11.178
this is an awful,
toxic creature.

08:11.220 --> 08:13.518
Fortunately, I don't need
to sleep with her again

08:13.560 --> 08:15.881
to get her out of my life,
I just need to leave.

08:17.690 --> 08:19.692
Marchioness.

08:21.160 --> 08:23.765
(indistinct radio transmission)

08:26.670 --> 08:28.535
Looking for
something to solve?

08:30.170 --> 08:31.967
My brother
makes you uncomfortable.

08:32.010 --> 08:34.308
Your posture stiffens subtly
whenever he gets close.

08:34.340 --> 08:36.672
I'm pretty sure it doesn't.
I suspected

08:36.710 --> 08:39.247
he would try to sleep with you
while we were in London,

08:39.280 --> 08:41.077
Is that what happened?
No.

08:41.120 --> 08:42.678
Were his advances ungentlemanly
in some way?

08:42.720 --> 08:44.210
There were no advances,
and I can't believe

08:44.250 --> 08:45.786
that's what
you want to talk about.

08:45.820 --> 08:46.809
Your brother had leukemia,

08:46.860 --> 08:49.249
and he didn't tell you
about it.

08:49.290 --> 08:51.326
I know if that happened to me,
I would be hurt

08:51.360 --> 08:53.225
and furious and sad and worried.

08:55.900 --> 08:57.322
I feel annoyed.

08:57.370 --> 08:58.598
Annoyed?

08:58.630 --> 09:00.166
Profoundly.

09:00.200 --> 09:01.667
Of course Mycroft's
spiritual awakening

09:01.700 --> 09:03.634
is tied to some sort of illness.

09:03.670 --> 09:05.228
The man has never met a clich

09:05.270 --> 09:06.828
he didn't have
a head-on collision with.

09:06.880 --> 09:09.678
(doorbell ringing)

09:09.710 --> 09:11.701
(sighs)

09:20.990 --> 09:22.855
Hello.

09:22.890 --> 09:24.755
I know it's late; I'm sorry.

09:26.860 --> 09:28.851
(door closes)

09:33.840 --> 09:35.831
Pleasant.

09:39.140 --> 09:40.698
I owe you an apology.

09:40.740 --> 09:42.105
Obviously, I should've told you.

09:42.140 --> 09:44.005
You needed bone marrow.

09:44.050 --> 09:46.769
A sibling is
the most likely match by far.

09:48.250 --> 09:50.684
I'm trying
to be less stubborn now.

09:50.720 --> 09:53.382
I think... I hope my illness

09:53.420 --> 09:54.956
has made me
a more compassnonate,

09:54.990 --> 09:56.821
better person.
Well, of course you do.

09:56.860 --> 09:58.054
You're following
the same narrative

09:58.090 --> 10:00.058
all venal people do
when they get sick.

10:00.100 --> 10:01.852
A lot of people may go
through the same thing,

10:01.900 --> 10:03.697
but it doesn't make it
less real.

10:03.730 --> 10:05.129
It's like an addiction
in that sense,

10:05.170 --> 10:06.762
I'd imagine.

10:06.800 --> 10:08.290
You asked how Nigella

10:08.340 --> 10:10.706
got back into my life.

10:10.740 --> 10:12.332
When I was diagnosed,

10:12.370 --> 10:13.974
she got in touch,

10:14.010 --> 10:16.672
asked if there was anything
she could do to help.

10:16.710 --> 10:19.008
When she learned I was looking
for a bone marrow donor,

10:19.050 --> 10:20.915
she organized a drive
to find one.

10:20.950 --> 10:23.817
Turned it into a cause,
got the whole posh crowd

10:23.850 --> 10:26.148
she was running
around with involved.

10:26.190 --> 10:28.852
I found my match because of her.

10:28.890 --> 10:30.323
One good turn deserves another.

10:30.360 --> 10:32.794
Yes, I suppose it does.

10:32.830 --> 10:34.320
In any case, I don't think

10:34.360 --> 10:36.055
this is about the quality
of Nigella's character.

10:36.100 --> 10:37.920
I think this is
about you and me.

10:39.400 --> 10:42.699
If we help her,
it will prove tangibly

10:42.740 --> 10:44.662
that we've put
this whole thing behind us.

10:46.740 --> 10:48.332
Or if you're still
feeling stubborn,

10:48.380 --> 10:51.406
you can just tell yourself
it's about solving a murder.

10:53.950 --> 10:56.817
So, Detective Bell said
two NYPD consultants

10:56.850 --> 10:58.078
would be coming out.

10:58.120 --> 11:00.281
Two did; we brought
a restaurateur with us.

11:00.320 --> 11:02.925
He also said
you'd be moving Silver Blaze

11:02.960 --> 11:04.279
to the NYPD stables?

11:04.330 --> 11:05.979
Yes, it seems the best way
to safeguard

11:06.030 --> 11:07.952
against further
possible attacks.

11:08.000 --> 11:09.319
So what happened here?

11:09.360 --> 11:11.089
Be thorough.

11:11.130 --> 11:13.792
Well, Dalton Ladd
parked his car there.

11:13.840 --> 11:15.193
He'd been out for a drink
with his friend Asa,

11:15.240 --> 11:16.867
who waited in the car

11:16.910 --> 11:19.708
while Mr. Ladd went
to give the horse his shot.

11:19.740 --> 11:22.208
He came upon a guy
trying to pick the lock.

11:22.240 --> 11:24.447
Asa said he was about
six feet tall,

11:24.480 --> 11:26.744
but he couldn't
see much more than that.

11:26.780 --> 11:28.839
Guy fires twice, he takes off
and he leaves his bag.

11:28.880 --> 11:31.144
Now, the owner had been
getting ready for bed.

11:31.190 --> 11:33.158
He heard the gunshots.

11:33.190 --> 11:34.885
He comes out with a shotgun,

11:34.920 --> 11:36.888
but, by that time,
the killer

11:36.930 --> 11:38.818
had reached
that tree line.

11:38.860 --> 11:40.350
Were there any
prints on the lock?

11:40.400 --> 11:41.856
Yeah. Too many.

11:41.900 --> 11:44.027
People are in and out of here
all the time,

11:44.070 --> 11:45.469
so no prints of value.

11:45.500 --> 11:47.968
So, did the owner
pursue the gunman?

11:48.000 --> 11:49.297
Yeah.

11:49.340 --> 11:50.864
Stayed on him for
about a quarter mile,

11:50.910 --> 11:52.775
till he reached
a clearing in the woods.

11:52.810 --> 11:54.801
But when he got there,
the guy was just gone.

11:56.810 --> 11:57.879
Sorry, it'd be bet...
could you just

11:57.910 --> 11:59.207
stay out of the eye line here?

11:59.250 --> 12:01.138
You're joking.
I was just standing here.

12:01.180 --> 12:02.408
Yes, that's the problem.

12:02.450 --> 12:04.884
Oh, could you show
us the clearing?

12:06.150 --> 12:08.880
So, like I said,
the owner chased him this far.

12:08.920 --> 12:10.979
But when he got here,
the guy was just gone.

12:11.030 --> 12:12.918
How much of a lead
did the gunman have?

12:12.960 --> 12:15.758
Well, the owner says he was
about a hundred yards behind.

12:15.800 --> 12:17.859
I know-- there's no way
that the gunman

12:17.900 --> 12:19.936
would've had time to make it
clear across the field.

12:19.970 --> 12:21.767
But I figure...

12:21.800 --> 12:24.303
the owner was further back from
the gunman than he thought.

12:24.340 --> 12:26.069
Yes, that's one possible
explanation.

12:26.110 --> 12:27.475
Another possible explanation

12:27.510 --> 12:28.932
is that he didn't
disappear at all,

12:28.980 --> 12:30.345
he just took
to higher ground,

12:30.380 --> 12:32.348
to see how many people
were following him

12:32.380 --> 12:34.416
and then planned
his escape.

12:34.450 --> 12:36.987
These trees are over
a hundred years old.

12:37.020 --> 12:38.089
There's no low-hanging branches.

12:38.120 --> 12:39.849
But this young oak
would work.

12:42.120 --> 12:44.384
He would have to hoist
himself up, off that branch.

12:44.430 --> 12:46.921
Yes, which means
he had to grab it.

12:48.430 --> 12:50.091
Right.

12:50.130 --> 12:52.394
Fortunately,
the bark is smooth

12:52.430 --> 12:54.364
on top.

13:17.860 --> 13:18.986
There.

13:19.030 --> 13:21.055
(camera clicks)

13:22.560 --> 13:25.199
I'll wager these are the
fingerprints of our murderer.

13:26.570 --> 13:28.834
There's one missing.

13:28.870 --> 13:30.406
The man we're looking for

13:30.440 --> 13:33.034
is missing the ring finger
from his left hand.

13:33.080 --> 13:35.537
Should we see if he's
been arrested before?

13:38.910 --> 13:41.049
Right. Let's see what
a would-be horse assassin

13:41.080 --> 13:42.547
brings on his rounds,
shall we?

13:44.090 --> 13:45.580
Mycroft,
if you'd like to be useful

13:45.620 --> 13:47.212
as something other
than a means of transportation,

13:47.260 --> 13:48.454
feel free to take notes.

13:48.490 --> 13:50.082
That policeman in Ulster County

13:50.130 --> 13:52.382
said we could look in the bag,
not take it away.

13:52.430 --> 13:54.250
Yes, well, I find it
best not to ask.

13:54.300 --> 13:55.858
They can get
quite territorial

13:55.900 --> 13:57.561
when you say you want
to take evidence with you.

13:57.600 --> 13:59.932
They certainly weren't using
it to solve any crimes.

14:01.940 --> 14:03.635
Two sets of lock picks...

14:03.670 --> 14:07.106
one very large knife...

14:07.140 --> 14:09.438
three syringes
bundled in duct tape

14:09.480 --> 14:11.402
and one map of Ulster County.

14:16.380 --> 14:18.848
Map has pin impressions on it.

14:26.560 --> 14:28.152
WATSON:
2501.

14:28.200 --> 14:29.656
Maybe an address?

14:29.700 --> 14:31.065
HOLMES:
Not a useful one.

14:32.700 --> 14:34.668
BELL: You guys are
swimming in some
deep water here.

14:34.700 --> 14:36.964
There's a_hit
on your prInts,

14:37.010 --> 14:39.934
